{{about|the academic field|the peer-reviewed journal|Developmental Science}}
'''Developmental science''' is an [[interdisciplinary]] scientific field that synthesizes perspectives from [[biology]], [[psychology]], and [[sociology]] in order to understand behavioral and psychological aspects of [[human development (psychology)|human development]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Bronfenbrenner |first=Urie |authorlink=Urie Bronfenbrenner|last2=Evans |first2=Gary W. |date=January 2000 |title=Developmental Science in the 21st Century: Emerging Questions, Theoretical Models, Research Designs and Empirical Findings |url=http://doi.wiley.com/10.1111/1467-9507.00114 |journal=[[Social Development (journal)|Social Development]] |language=en |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=115–125 |doi=10.1111/1467-9507.00114 |issn=0961-205X}}</ref> The field of developmental science "...is not limited to simply describing [[Deviance (sociology)|deviant behavior]] at a specific age, but rather examines the dynamic interplay of biopsychosocial risk and protective conditions in the course of development over an individual’s lifespan."<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ewi-psy.fu-berlin.de/en/einrichtungen/arbeitsbereiche/entwicklungswissenschaft/index.html |title=Developmental Science and Applied Developmental Psychology |date=2006-03-06 |website=[[Free University of Berlin]] |language=en |access-date=2018-08-03}}</ref> It is based on theories previously developed by such psychologists as [[Jean Piaget]], [[Heinz Werner (psychologist)|Heinz Werner]], and [[Lev Vygotsky]], as well as on [[dynamic systems theory]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=van Geert |first=Paul |author-link=Paul van Geert |date=April 1998 |title=We almost had a great future behind us: The contribution of non-linear dynamics to developmental-science-in-the-making |url=http://doi.wiley.com/10.1111/1467-7687.00020 |journal=[[Developmental Science]] |language=en |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=143–159 |doi=10.1111/1467-7687.00020 |issn=1363-755X}}</ref> In recent years, the field has undergone a [[paradigm shift]] away from [[reductionism]] to one based on complex, interacting systems, with an increasing emphasis on change over time.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Aldwin |first=Carolyn M. |date=2014-10-02 |title=Rethinking Developmental Science |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/15427609.2014.967045 |journal=[[Research in Human Development]] |language=en |volume=11 |issue=4 |pages=247–254 |doi=10.1080/15427609.2014.967045 |issn=1542-7609 |pmc=4295790 |pmid=25598750}}</ref>

