{{Infobox academic division |name = Faculty of Mathematics |native_name = |former_names = |type = [[Faculty (division)|Faculty]] |affiliation = [[University of Waterloo]] |image_name = File:WaterlooMathBuilding.jpg |image_size = 230px |caption = Mathematics and Computer Building |established = {{Start date|1967|1|1}} |closed = <!-- {{End date|YYYY}} --> |city = [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]] |province = [[Ontario]] |country = Canada |coor = |dean = [[Stephen M. Watt]] |academic_staff = |students = |undergrad = 6,936<ref name=headcount>{{cite web|url=https://uwaterloo.ca/institutional-analysis-planning/university-data-and-statistics/student-data/student-headcounts|title=Student Headcounts|website=Institutional Analysis and Planning|publisher=University of Waterloo|access-date=3 November 2018}}</ref> |postgrad = 420{{r|headcount}} |doctoral = 337{{r|headcount}} |alumni = > 31,000<ref name=history>{{cite web|title=Our history|website=Faculty of Mathematics|publisher=University of Waterloo|access-date=3 November 2018|url=https://uwaterloo.ca/math/about/our-history}}</ref> |motto = |motto_lang = |motto_eng = |symbol = Pink tie |website = {{URL|https://uwaterloo.ca/math}} |logo = [[File:Waterloo-Mathematics.svg|200px]] }}
The '''Faculty of Mathematics''' is one of six faculties of the [[University of Waterloo]] in [[Waterloo, Ontario]], offering over 500 courses in [[mathematics]], [[statistics]] and [[computer science]]. The Faculty also houses the [[David R. Cheriton School of Computer Science]], formerly the Faculty's computer science department.
==History== The Faculty was founded on January 1, 1967, a successor to the University of Waterloo's Department of Mathematics, which had grown to be the largest department in the [[University of Waterloo Faculty of Arts|Faculty of Arts]] under the chairmanship of [[Ralph Gordon Stanton|Ralph Stanton]] (and included such influential professors as [[W. T. Tutte]]).{{r|history}} Initially located in the Physics building, the Faculty was moved in May 1968 into the newly constructed Mathematics and Computing (MC) Building. Inspired by Stanton's famously gaudy ties, the students draped a large pink tie over the MC Building on the occasion of its opening, which later became a symbol of the Faculty.<ref name=pinktie>{{cite web|title=Legend of the Pink Tie|url=https://www.math.uwaterloo.ca/navigation/About/pinktie.shtml|date=17 August 2011|website=Faculty of Mathematics|publisher=University of Waterloo|access-date=3 November 2018}}</ref>
At the time of its founding, the Faculty included five departments: [[Computer science|Applied Analysis and Computer Science]], [[Applied Mathematics]], [[Combinatorics|Combinatorics and Optimization]], [[Pure Mathematics]], and [[Statistics]]. In 1975 the Department of Applied Analysis and Computer Science became simply the Department of Computer Science; in 2005 it became the [[David R. Cheriton School of Computer Science]]. The Statistics Department also was later renamed the Department of Statistics and Actuarial Science.{{r|history}}
The Faculty of Mathematics finished construction of a third building, Mathematics 3 (M3), in 2011. It now houses the Department of Statistics and Actuarial Science and a large lecture hall.
==Academics== ===Degrees=== The Faculty of Mathematics grants the [[Bachelor of Mathematics|BMath]] (Bachelor of Mathematics) degree for most of its undergraduate programs. Computer Science undergraduates can generally choose between graduating with a BMath or a [[Bachelor of Computer Science|BCS]] (Bachelor of Computer Science) degree. The former requires more coursework in mathematics. Specialized degrees exist for the [[Software Engineering]] program (the [[Bachelor of Software Engineering|BSE]], or Bachelor of Software Engineering) and Computing and Financial Management ([[Bachelor of Computing|BCFM]], or Bachelor of Computing and Financial Management). Postgraduate students are generally awarded an [[Master of Mathematics|MMath]] (Master of Mathematics) or [[PhD]].
===Rankings=== In the 2018 [[QS World University Rankings]], the University of Waterloo was ranked 39th globally for Mathematics (and 3rd in Canada) and 31st globally for Computer Science (and 2nd in Canada).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2018/mathematics|title=QS World University Rankings by Subject 2018: Mathematics|website=[[QS World University Rankings]]|access-date=3 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2018/computer-science-information-systems|title=QS World University Rankings by Subject 2018: Computer Science & Informational Systems|website=[[QS World University Rankings]]|access-date=3 November 2018}}</ref> The University was ranked third in Canada for Mathematics and second in Canada for Computer Science in 2018 by the [[Maclean's|Maclean's University Rankings]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Best mathematics universities in Canada: 2018 rankings|date=30 November 2017|newspaper=[[Maclean's]]|url=https://www.macleans.ca/education/best-mathematics-universities-in-canada-2018-rankings/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Best computer science universities in Canada: 2018 ranking|date=30 November 2017|newspaper=[[Maclean's]]|url=https://www.macleans.ca/education/best-computer-science-universities-in-canada-2018-ranking/}}</ref>
==Student life== [[Image:UW-MathFaculty-PinkTie.jpg|230px|thumb|right|The Pink Tie]] Students in the Faculty of Mathematics are represented by the Mathematics Society (MathSoc), which represents student interests to the university, operates the Math Coffee and Donut Shop, publishes the Faculty newspaper ''mathNEWS'', and runs student services including an exam bank and lounge space.<ref>{{cite web|title=MathSoc Services|url=http://mathsoc.uwaterloo.ca/Services|website=University of Waterloo Mathematics Society|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref>
[[Pi Day]] is celebrated by the Department in each term: on 14 March (3/14), on 22 July (22/7, [[Pi Approximation Day]]), and on 10 November (the 314th day of the year). Typical activities include throwing pie at MathSoc executives and/or popular professors, viewing mathematics-related films, competing in [[pi]] recitation contests, and eating pie (on 22/7, cake is served instead, which is approximately pie).
===Tie Guard=== A yearly tradition at the University of Waterloo, a group of senior math students volunteer for the position of Tie Guard each year, and are selected by the [[University of Waterloo Federation of Students]] representatives from the Faculty of Mathematics. It is expected that the appointed Tie Guard volunteers will be on hand 24 hours a day for the duration of the orientation week, to guard the Faculty's mascot (a 40 foot pink tie which hangs off the side of the building) and to provide [[first aid]] and information to incoming students.{{r|pinktie}}
The Tie Guard was founded in 1994 after several previous attempts on the Pink Tie resulted in both damaged mascots and injuries to students, the most notorious of which was the Tie Liberation Organization (TLO) kidnapping in 1988. In more recent years the tie guard has expanded and now several students are appointed to the Tie Guard each year. A new pink tie was draped over the Mathematics 3 Building in 2011.
